            "creation_date": 1327376199,
            "body": "<p>Functors encapsulate functions as objects.  You can pass them around to other objects to get things done.<\/p>\n\n<p>Think <a href=\"http://java.dzone.com/articles/design-patterns-command\" rel=\"nofollow\">Gang of Four Command Pattern<\/a>.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 8981724,
            "question_id": 8981691
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b2ee5980501f21314923f751e4740446?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 95764,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 260633,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/260633/dev",
                "reputation": 12266,
                "display_name": "Dev",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1327376419,
            "creation_date": 1327376419,
            "body": "<p>If an object does not implement <code>Comparable<\/code> you can write an implementation of <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/util/Comparator.html\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>Comparator<\/code><\/a> to achieve the same effect. <code>Comparator<\/code> is, in fact, the example given in the wikipedia arctile about <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Function_object#In_Java\" rel=\"nofollow\">functors in Java<\/a>. If the an object is not <code>Comparable<\/code> it can still be sorted by <code>Collections.sort(Collection, Comparator)<\/code> by providing a relevant <code>Comparator<\/code> implementation.<\/p>\n\n<p>The interface <code>Comparator<\/code> is an example of a functor. Implementations of it can be passed around for other objects or methods to use to do something (In this case compare two objects).<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 8981747,
            "question_id": 8981691
        }
    ],
